                <p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The Rank of a Matrix is the maximum nu=
mber of </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/linear-indepe=
ndence/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span>linearly independent</spa=
n></a><span> rows or columns in a matrix. It essentially determines the dim=
ensionality of the vector space formed by the rows or columns of the matrix=
.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>It helps determine:</span></p><ul><li valu=
e=3D"1"><span>If a system of linear equations has solutions.</span></li><li=
 value=3D"2"><span>The "usefulness" of rows or columns contributes to the m=
atrix's information.</span></li></ul><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"ht=
tps://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20240122123319/Rank-and-Nu=
llity.jpg" alt=3D"Rank-and-Nullity" width=3D"587" height=3D"471"><figcaptio=
n>Rank and Nullity of a Matrix</figcaption></figure><p dir=3D"ltr"><br><spa=
n>The rank of a matrix is denoted using =CF=81(A), where A is any matrix. T=
hus, the number of rows of a matrix is a limit on the rank of the matrix, w=
hich means the rank of the matrix cannot exceed the total number of rows in=
 a matrix. </span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>For example</strong></b><sp=
an>, if a matrix is of the order 3=C3=973, then the maximum rank of a matri=
x can be 3. </span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Note: If a matrix h=
as all rows with zero elements, then the rank of a matrix is said to be zer=
o.</span></p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"nullity-of-matrix" style=3D"text-align:=
left"><span>Nullity of Matrix</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>In a given ma=
trix, the number of vectors in the null space is called the nullity of the =
matrix, or it can also be defined as the dimension of the null space of the=
 given matrix. </span></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Desktop_InContent_ATF_728x280" =
style=3D"text-align: center; margin: 10px 0px;"></div><blockquote><p dir=3D=
"ltr" style=3D"text-align: left;"><span>Total columns in a matrix =3D Rank =
+ Nullity</span></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"rank-of-a-matrix-formulas" style=
=3D"text-align:left"><span>Finding Rank of a Matrix</span></h2><p dir=3D"lt=
r"><span>3 methods can be used to get the rank of any given matrix. These m=
ethods are as follows:</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Minor Method</sp=
an></li><li value=3D"2"><span>Using Elementary Operations</span></li></ul><=
h3 id=3D"minor-method" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Using Minor Method</=
span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>To find the rank of a matrix using the </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/dsa/minors-and-cofactors/" targe=
t=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span>minor method</span></a><span>, the foll=
owing steps are followed:</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Calculate the=
 determinant of the matrix (say A). If det(A) =E2=89=A0 0, then the rank of=
 matrix A =3D order of matrix A.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>If det(A)=
 =3D 0, then the rank of the matrix is equal to the order of the maximum po=
ssible nonzero minor of the matrix.</span></li></ul><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Le=
t us understand how to find the rank of a matrix using the minor method.</s=
pan></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"overflow: auto hidden; padding: 2px;"><b><s=
